<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <%- include('partials/head') %>

  <body>
    <%- include('partials/nav') %>

    <main>
      <section class="food-support-hero">
        <h1>Community Initiatives in Ladywood</h1>
        <p>Exploring the community-led projects and events shaping life in Ladywood.</p>
      </section>

        <section class="food-support-cta">
        <h2>Looking for community events near you?</h2>
        <p>Browse community events and initiatives listed in the CommunityLink directory.</p>
        <a href="/services?category=Community Events" class="btn-services">View Community Events</a>
      </section>

      <section class="food-info">

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>A Hub of Community Activity</h2>
          <p>
            Ladywood is an area of deep social connections and a hub of creativity and community.
            Despite facing significant challenges including deprivation, budget cuts and the
            effects of climate change, residents and organisations in Ladywood continue to come
            together to build a stronger, more resilient neighbourhood.
          </p>
          <p>
            Community organisations across Ladywood run a wide range of initiatives — from food
            growing and repair cafes, to neighbourhood supper clubs, canal activities and street
            parties. These events play a vital role in reducing social isolation, building trust
            between neighbours, and connecting people with the support they need.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>CIVIC SQUARE and Neighbourhood Building</h2>
          <p>
            CIVIC SQUARE has been organising in Ladywood for over 10 years, working to co-build
            civic infrastructure that is owned and governed by the people who live there. Their
            work centres on a key question: how can our neighbourhood become a thriving place,
            home to thriving people, whilst respecting the wellbeing of all people and the health
            of the whole planet?
          </p>
          <p>
            Their Neighbourhood Public Square project at Port Loop is being built as a space for
            the whole community — including a Cafe and Community Kitchen, Neighbourhood Town Hall,
            Library of Things, Cycle Hub, Studios and Meeting Rooms, and a Neighbourhood
            Microfactory. The site is designed to be open, inclusive and collectively owned by
            the neighbourhood in perpetuity.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Connecting People Through Events</h2>
          <p>
            Regular community events are central to life in Ladywood. CIVIC SQUARE runs a
            Neighbourhood Supper Club — a regular gathering where local organisers are invited
            to connect with each other and their neighbours. The Floating Front Room, a
            neighbourhood cafe operating from a canal barge, reopened in Spring 2025 as a
            weekly space for lunch, cake and coffee.
          </p>
          <p>
            During the COVID-19 pandemic, Ladywood proved to be a formidable hub for mutual aid.
            Neighbours and community organisations stepped up to distribute food packages and
            support vulnerable residents, demonstrating the strength of community connections
            when they are most needed.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Growing, Repairing and Creating Together</h2>
          <p>
            Community initiatives in Ladywood span many areas of everyday life. Warm Earth
            connects people through gardening and food growing, running monthly events where
            residents share food, music and stories from different backgrounds. Repair cafes have
            popped up across the city, keeping valuable materials out of landfill while bringing
            people together around shared skills.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Birmingham Food Revolution showcases community dining projects, composting
            initiatives, surplus food redistribution and cooking classes. Growing spaces give
            diverse communities the opportunity to grow culturally important produce and share
            knowledge across generations.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Challenges Facing the Community</h2>
          <p>
            Many residents in Ladywood have caring responsibilities or work longer hours due to
            the cost of living crisis, making it harder to engage with community activities.
            Budget cuts by Birmingham City Council have led to the closure of libraries, community
            centres and arts spaces — reducing the infrastructure available for people to come
            together. 25 out of 36 libraries across the city are set to close.
          </p>
          <p>
            Despite this, community groups continue to find creative ways to reach people —
            through leafleting, door-knocking, social media and word of mouth. The Save Birmingham
            campaign is working to protect heritage, cultural and community spaces, and explore
            community-owned solutions for public services that are fair and sustainable.
          </p>
        </div>

      </section>

    

    </main>

    <%- include('partials/footer') %>
  </body>
</html>